CERN Open Hardware Licence Version 2 - Strongly Reciprocal

Preamble

CERN has developed this licence to promote collaboration among
hardware designers and to provide a legal tool which supports the
freedom to use, study, modify, share and distribute hardware designs
and products based on those designs. Version 2 of the CERN Open
Hardware Licence comes in three variants: CERN-OHL-P (permissive); and
two reciprocal licences: CERN-OHL-W (weakly reciprocal) and this
licence, CERN-OHL-S (strongly reciprocal).

The strongly reciprocal variant of the CERN OHL is intended for use in
cases where the Licensor wishes to ensure that all Derivatives of the
Covered Source remain freely available under the terms of the licence
and that products incorporating Covered Source or Derivatives thereof
be made available to any recipient under the terms of section 3 of
this licence.

Please read the licence carefully before using it or applying it to
your hardware design or product.

                       TERMS AND CONDITIONS

0 Definitions

  0.1 'Licence' means this CERN-OHL-S.

  0.2 'Compatible Licence' means

       a) any version of the CERN-OHL-S, or

       b) a licence which permits its licensees to treat the text of
          its terms and conditions as if it were a later version of
          the CERN-OHL-S, provided that such licence:

            i) also provides for the patent non-aggression clause
               under section 8 of this licence; and
           ii) also provides for a notice and disclaimer requirement
               under sections 5 and 6 of this licence.

  0.3 'Source' means information such as design materials or digital
      code which can be applied to Make or test a Product or to
      prepare a Product for use, Conveyance or sale, regardless of
      its medium or how it is expressed. It may include Notices.

  0.4 'Covered Source' means Source that is explicitly made available
      under this Licence.

  0.5 'Product' means any device, component, work or physical object,
      whether in finished or intermediate form, arising from the use,
      application or processing of Covered Source.

  0.6 'Make' means to create or configure something, whether by
      manufacture, assembly, compiling, loading or applying Covered
      Source or another Product or otherwise.

  0.7 'Available Component' means any part, sub-assembly, library or
      code that:

       a) is licensed to the recipient under terms that permit it to
          be used, modified, Conveyed, and Used to make a Product;

       b) is generally commercially available; and

       c) is reasonably acquirable by the recipient without undue
          effort or resources.

      An Available Component need not be licensed under this Licence. A
      Product which comprises only Available Components is not a
      Covered Source.

  0.8 'External Material' means anything which is:

       a) incorporated into a Product, or into Covered Source; or

       b) used to Make a Product, but which is not itself a Product; or

       c) incorporated into, or used to Make a Product which is not
          itself a Product;

      and which is not part of the Covered Source.

  0.9 'Derivative' means any work which is derived from or based upon
      all or part of the Covered Source, including a circuit or
      mechanical design derived from the Covered Source, or any
      documentation based on or incorporating the Covered Source.

  0.10 'Convey' means to communicate to the public or to distribute.

  0.11 'Upstream Licensee' means the Licensor(s) who provided to the
       Licensor the Licence for the Covered Source. Any Upstream
       Licensor is not a party to this Licence.

  0.12 'Notice' means copyright, acknowledgement and trademark notices,
       references to this Licence, and modifications to the Source, in
       each case as included in or attached to the Covered Source.

  0.13 'Licensor' means any person who creates or modifies Covered
       Source. A person may be a Licensor and a recipient at the same
       time.

  0.14 'Recipient' means any person who receives the Covered Source,
       including all Contributors.

  0.15 'Contributor' means any person who modifies the Covered Source.

  0.16 'User' means any person who Makes a Product.

1 Applicability

  1.1 This Licence governs the use, copying, modification, Conveying
      of Covered Source and Products, and the Making of Products. By
      exercising any right granted under this Licence, You irrevocably
      accept these terms and conditions.

  1.2 This Licence is granted by the Licensor directly to You, and
      shall apply worldwide and without limitation in time.

  1.3 You shall not attempt to restrict by contract or otherwise the
      rights granted under this Licence to other Recipients.

  1.4 This Licence is not intended to restrict fair use, fair dealing,
      or any other legally recognised limitation or exception to
      copyright.

2 Internally Used Source

  2.1 You may use Covered Source internally for the purposes of study
      and research without obligation to comply with section 3 of
      this Licence.

  2.2 Any Modifications made by You to the Covered Source must be
      documented in the Source in a human-readable form and dated.

3 Conditions for Conveying Covered Source

  3.1 You may Convey verbatim copies of the Covered Source in any
      medium, provided You retain all Notices.

  3.2 You may Convey Covered Source, with or without modification,
      provided that You:

       a) retain Notices as required under section 3.1;

       b) add a Notice to the modified Covered Source stating that You
          have modified it, with the date and brief description of how
          You have modified it;

       c) add a Notice to the Covered Source prominently stating that
          it is available under this Licence, with the text of, or the
          URL or address of, this Licence;

       d) make the Covered Source (including any modifications) and
          any Notices available under the terms of this Licence to
          anyone who comes into possession of the Covered Source.

  3.3 You may only Convey Covered Source under the terms of this
      Licence. You may not impose any further restrictions on the
      exercise of the rights granted or affirmed under this Licence.

  3.4 If You Convey Covered Source You must provide to each recipient
      a written offer valid for three years, or for as long as You
      Convey the Product, to give anyone who comes into possession of
      the Covered Source a copy of the Covered Source at no charge
      with the rights conferred by this Licence.

  3.5 You may incorporate the Covered Source into a larger work,
      provided that the larger work contains Covered Source under this
      Licence and is released under a Compatible Licence.

  3.6 You may not apply legal terms or technological measures that
      legally restrict a recipient from exercising any right granted
      under this Licence.

4 Conditions for Making Products

  4.1 You may Make Products, and Convey them to anyone, provided that:

       a) You ensure that each Product which You Make contains and
          displays the following Notice prominently:

              "This Product is based on Covered Source licensed under
               the CERN-OHL-S v2 (https://ohwr.org/cern_ohl_s_v2.txt)
               by [name of Licensor] and others."

       b) You make the Covered Source (including any Modifications
          made by You) and any Notices available under the terms of
          this Licence to anyone who comes into possession of the
          Product.

  4.2 If You Make a Product which incorporates External Material not
      covered by any of the rights granted under this Licence, You
      must ensure that such External Material is clearly identified
      as such in the Product.

5 Notices

  5.1 You must retain all Notices as provided in the Covered Source,
      including in particular the copyright, authorship and
      contribution Notices.

  5.2 If it is not possible to retain Notices in a particular form
      (such as a physical label), You must instead provide such
      Notices in a form that is reasonable in the circumstances, for
      example in the Product documentation.

